8 election numbers that show Donald Trump in real light
Some have tried to describe him as a person who often changes his mind.
The others waved their hands like a misguided joke.
And some are preparing for implosion.
But whatever republicans are trying to pull Donald Trump down from the top of the polls, they're failing (so far).
10 of the last 11 national polls show Donald Trump in a double-digit lead, and some are seriously questioning what that means for the real estate mogul's nominating chances.
Of course, it is only the beginning of the election cycle.
None of this says that Trump is likely to win the Republican nomination.
Experts point out that at this time in 2011, Rick Perry's leadership had paved the way for Herman Cain's rise, and in the end neither of them won a single position in the nominating process.
There are many reasons why he might come across in the general election.
But outside groups like Jeb Bush's super PAC and the economic conservative group Club for Growth recognize Trump's will to hold on and are starting to unload their dollars to overthrow him.
Here are some recent poll numbers that suggest that the real estate mogul is not just a far-ed phase:
Trump's favorability rating has reversed 180 degrees.
Just before Donald Trump announced his candidacy in mid-June, a Monmouth University poll showed that only two out of 10 Republicans had a positive view of the real estate mogul.
By mid-July, it was already 40 percent.
At the beginning of August, it was 52 percent.
Now six out of 10 Republicans have a favorable view of Donald Trump.
Roughly three in 10 say they have a negative opinion of him.
And these numbers hold up in the early stages.
After a Quinnipiac University poll last week, it was found that 60 percent of Republicans had a positive opinion of Trump.
Two-thirds of GOP voters would be happy with Trump as the nominee.
In a CNN/ORC poll conducted last week, 67 percent of Republicans said they would either be "excited" or "satisfied" with Trump as the nominee.
Only two in 10 said they would be "outraged" at his candidacy.
Only Ben Carson generates roughly the same level of enthusiasm as Trump (43 percent said they would be "thrilled" against 40 percent who say the same about Trump).
The next closest in the level of enthusiasm?
Marco Rubio with only 21 percent.
On the other hand, 47 percent of Republican voters say they would be "dissatisfied" or "upset" if gov. Jeb Bush became the nominee.
Most Republicans don't see Trump's temperament as a problem.
While Donald Trump has been widely criticized for his bombast and insults, 52 percent of Republican voters nationwide are inclined to think that the real estate mogul has the right temperament for the presidency, according to an ABC News/Washington Post poll released Monday.
The same number is held in the Iowa State Senatorial Caucus, which is the first in the country where 52 percent of Republicans think he has a leadership personality, according to Quinnipiac last week.
Still, 44 percent think he doesn't have the personality to serve effectively, and nearly 6 in 10 independents say his temperament doesn't belong in the White House, according to ABC/Post.
Republican voters are getting used to the idea.
When they put on their scholarly hats, Republican voters think Trump is the real candidate.
When asked who would most likely win the GOP nomination, four in 10 said Trump would be the best choice, according to a CNN/ORC poll last week.
That's a change from late July, when four out of 10 bet their money on Jeb Bush.
Full disclosure: GOP voters haven't had the brightest crystal ball in the past.
By this time last cycle, 4 in 10 Republicans had chosen Rick Perry as the winner of the race, compared to 28 percent for Mitt Romney's eventual nomination.
Yet it turns out that a certain number of GOP voters see the Trump campaign as credible.
Even as Republicans rallie around another candidate, Trump still beats almost everyone.
Some pundits point out that the fragmented field is likely to contribute to Trump's leadership, while anti-Trump support is diffusely distributed among more than a dozen other candidates.
But a Monmouth University poll in early September shows that in a hypothetical head-to-head matchup between Trump and most other Republican candidates, Trump almost always gets majority support.
He leads Carly Fiorina by 13 points, Marco Rubio by 14 points, Walker by 15 points, Jeb Bush by 19 points, and finally Rand Paul, John Kasich, Chris Christie by 33 points each.
He's in a dead race with Ted Cruz.
The only candidate who beats him?
Ben Carson would lead the businessman by a wide 19 points in a hypothetical one-on-one game.
A bare majority of Donald Trump's supporters say they have already made up their minds.
A new CBS/NYT poll tuesday shows that only more than half of voters who support Trump say they won't change their minds.
Obviously, a lot of things can change that, and no one can really say that they've never changed their mind.
46 percent say they keep the back door open for a change among candidates.
Still, Trump's current strongest opponent is his outsider neurosurgeon Ben Carson, but voters who consider his opinion final would be twice as likely to vote for Trump.
Six out of 10 Republicans reportedly agree with Trump on the immigration issue.
Even since Donald Trump called immigrants from Mexico "rapists" in his campaign's announcing speech, immigration has still been a major and central topic of conversation for 2016.
Some fear that Trump's bombast will draw key Hispanic voters away from the Republican Party and damage the rebranding.
But according to a new ABC/Post poll released Monday, six out of 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration issues.
It seems that as long as the topic of immigration remains in the spotlight, Donald Trump will remain so.
Frustration with the government is reaching new highs.
Donald Trump and Ben Carson now receive roughly half of the support from Republican voters, especially given their outsider status.
Six out of 10 Republicans in a new ABC/Post poll released Monday say they want a political outsider rather than someone with government experience.
And they're also very angry with Washington.
A Des Moines Register/Bloomberg poll in Iowa a few weeks ago revealed that three out of four Republicans in Iowa are frustrated with Congressional Republicans, 54 percent are "dissatisfied" and 21 percent are "hellishly angry."
