Jeremy Corbyn will make his debut at Prime Minister's Questions
Since his election, Mr Corbyn's debut at PMQs has been widely expected
New Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn will make his Prime Minister's Questions debut later, and for the first time he will work with David Cameron.
Mr Corbyn will ask the first of his six assigned questions shortly after noon, while his performance is likely to be carefully scrutined by the media and MPs.
In a weekly statement, he called for "less theater and more facts."
He also stated that he could skip several sessions that he would leave to his colleagues.
The meeting will be the first parliamentary test of Mr Corby's leadership following his appointment to the shadow cabinet and his speech to the TUC's annual congress on Tuesday.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader's decision to stand quietly during the singing of the national anthem on Tuesday to mark the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain has been met with criticism from a number of Conservative MPs and has been the focus of several front-page stories.
Mr Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem attracted attention
A spokesman for Mr Corbyn said he would "stand in respectful silence" and would recognize "the heroism of the Royal Air Force in the Battle of Britain."
However, Mr Corbyn's shadow cabinet member, Owen Smith, told BBC Two's Newsnight programme that he would recommend the Labour leader sing the national anthem "regardless" of his belief that the monarchy should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers refused to serve on Mr Corbyn's top team, citing differences in the economy, defence and foreign affairs, and only less than a sixth of the parliamentary party originally supported him as leader.
BBC political correspondent Robin Brant says political differences at work are also "accumulating" following Mr Corbyn's appointment despite his position in the European Union and the government's benefit cap.
Mr Corbyl told the TUC conference that labor was putting forward amended proposals to remove the whole idea of a benefit cap.
Hours later, Mr Smith, the shadow work and pensions secretary, said the party had "very clearly" opposed the government's plans to reduce the cap from £26,000 to £23,000.
Mr Corbyn will be the fifth Labour leader facing David Cameron in the decade since his election as Tory leader.
The Labour leader, who has promised a different approach to politics, says he has ideas "from the crowd" for questions for Mr Cameron and has received more than 30,000 proposals.
The Islington North MP says PMQs are too confrontational and refrain from both "prompt responses" and gearing, and instead promises to focus on important issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges faced by young people.
Mr Corbyn claims that Angela Eagle, the shadow business secretary, will represent him at PMQs if he does not attend - such as when Mr Cameron travels abroad.
He also dropped the idea of letting other colleagues speak for him from time to time, as he said he had discussed the matter with Speaker of the House John Bercow.
When Mr Cameron became leader in 2005, he said he wanted to move away from the "Punch and Judy" style of politics, which was often associated with PMQs, but admitted a few years later that he had failed.
Since its first broadcast in 1990, PMQs have been seen as a key barometer of leaders' judgment, their leadership of the House and their position among other MPs, although critics have argued that they have become a caricature and far-reaching reforms are needed.
