Multiple sclerosis: it is not only the patients who matter, but also the will of the patient to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease, and a person with this diagnosis needs the care of a number of specialists: neurologist, physiotherapist, occupational ergotherapist, urologist, ophthalmologist, psychologist, psychiatrist and many other specialists.
However, it is not only about medical care, for example, women with multiple sclerosis also need consultations if they decide to have a child, social counselling, recommendations in housing arrangements, etc. are included in the care of these patients.
Yet all this is not enough: the development of the disease can be significantly influenced by the patient himself.
The more he actively fights the disease, the longer he can work and may not fundamentally change his lifestyle.
As doctors point out, the passivity of the sick frees up space for disease activity.
For example, regular movement has been shown to significantly delay the time when the patient needs some compensatory aid, such as a cane.
It is important that patients and their surroundings are not subject to various myths, such as that illness automatically leads them to end up in a wheelchair.
That's why the Give Yourself a Chance (www.bezmytu.cz) page was created, which is supported by the ongoing Give Yourself a Chance media campaign.
The most important person in the care of a patient with multiple sclerosis is a neurologist.
In multiple sclerosis, the adage twice that the sooner the disease begins to be treated, the more likely it is for the doctor to influence something.
This is because we have multiple sclerosis drugs at an inflammatory stage where the neurodegeneration process is not yet so strong.
The sooner we intervene, the greater the chance that we will be able to stop the disease and put off disability, explains Eva Medová from the Neurological Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
Rehabilitation care is very important in people with multiple sclerosis, which most often addresses weakening of the lower limbs or balance disorders.
Patients are worked on according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve walking, strengthen the pelvic floor, alleviate swallowing disorders or improve coordination.
"It is really individual, it depends on the specific problems of the patient," says Martina Kövári, Head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine at motol University Hospital.
People with multiple sclerosis suffer from the same disease, but it manifests itself in a slightly different way for everyone.
Rehabilitation can not stop the disease, but it can always alleviate its symptoms.
However, physical activity also strengthens the immune state of the organism, which is desirable in case of multiple sclerosis.
Another positive of regular exercise is that the sick check what they can do, and this strengthens their confidence.
"Endorphins are also washed out during exercise and make you feel good," says PhDr. Kamila Řasová from the Department of Rehabilitation Medicine at the Royal Vinohrady University Hospital.
By influencing the physical side, we act on the limbic system responsible for emotions.
This is how we directly interfere with the psyche and immune processes and stabilize the disease, he adds.
"Previously, these patients were so-called savers, today we know that they need a targeted load," says Prof. PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, Head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine at motol University Hospital.
The aim of physiotherapy is to ensure that a person can remain self-sufficient for as long as possible, including job placement.
Physiotherapists therefore work with occupational ergotherapists to give each person a compensatory aid tailored to him.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or psychiatrist.
They're in a difficult life situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, it shakes most people.
They experience shock, panic, fear.
They must respond to a great burden - loss of health.
With such a sore soul, we're supposed to go to someone, not try to carry everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them so that they eventually come to the conclusion that even with a handicap one can live a full life and that multiple sclerosis does not mean the end of life," says psychotherapist Renata Malinová - Schubertová from the Neurological Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
