MPs supported a larger share of the state's coal charges.
The change in mineral mining fees is intended to bring CZK 427 million more to the state coffers than in 2013.
According to the government, it is intended to have a neutral impact on the revenues of municipal budgets, as the fee is to be higher.
In the year before last, municipalities received approximately CZK 450 million from fees and CZK 150 million from the state budget.
From brown coal mining, municipalities were 200 million crowns and the state 66 million crowns.
The amendment also provides for an increase in the remuneration from mining premises with permitted mining to czk 1,000 per hectare per year.
The income from these payments is to continue to belong fully to the municipalities.
Minister of Industry Jan Mládek (ČSSD) told MPs that this would give municipalities between CZK 14 million and CZK 100 million a year instead of CZK 14 million.
The amount of mining fees will no longer be determined by law, but determined by the government by decree.
The remuneration is newly calculated as the product of the amount of mineral extracted and the rates for each type of mineral.
According to the government, the reason for the change is, among other things, the possibility of a flexible response to the current economic situation.
However, ODS MP Marek Benda warned that setting the fee by government regulation may not comply with the Constitution.
According to Minister Mládek, however, this is not a tax because the state is charging for minerals that are state property.
Only municipalities whose territories are affected by mining receive fees.
In the case of deep-sea coal mining, three quarters of the money will go to the municipality and a quarter to the state.
The ratio will be the same in the case of radioactive rock mining.
Some of the money collected by the state in mining fees will be assigned to the purpose.
For example, 28 percent will have to go to repair damage after mining or to provide mining rescue services.
The draft was criticised today by opposition MPs, who argued in particular that it would harm municipalities affected by mining and counties.
For example, Michal Kučera (TOP 09 and Mayors) warned that mining companies would no longer want to sponsor municipalities as before, because they would pay higher fees directly into the state budget.
"It is not possible to tunnel one of the poorest regions just to improve the budget," said David Kádner (Dawn), elected in the Ústí Region.
