"Sonogenetics", or control of brain cells using sound waves
This video shows how sound pulses affect the direction in which nematoes move.
Scientists have raised worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can control sound waves.
Tiny nematode changes direction when they are struck by sound pulses that are inaudible to the human ear.
Pulses work by switching cells of genetically modified motor neurons that are programmed to respond to these ultrasonic waves.
Related: Scientists can read and write brain activity using light
Scientists said these worms are a great example of a new methodology called sonogenetics, which uses ultrasound to activate brain, heart and muscle cells and activates outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that this method could one day replace deep brain stimulation - an invasive procedure in which electrodes that stimulate the brain are injected into the patient's brain. The method is used, for example, to treat symptoms of Parkinson's disease.
Nematode usually does not respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that the reaction occurs when it is placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
As he discovered, bubbles amplify ultrasonic waves, which then pass through the body of worms.
Reinforced ultrasonic waves act in the TRP-4 ion channels, which are located in the membranes of some worm cells.
Thanks to sound waves, these channels open and activate the cells they are connected to, according to a report in the journal Nature Communications.
To control nematoeisms using ultrasonic waves, Chalasani genetically modified worms so that some of their motor neurons contain TRP-4 ion channels.
When he then applied ultrasound to such modified worms, the sound waves were amplified by microbubs and transferred to worms, where modified motor neurons turned on.
The new method is similar in many ways to optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off using light.
But Chalasani said sonogenetics could have many advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent by optical fiber to the desired place in the brain, ultrasonic waves can penetrate the tissue without restriction and be sent directly to the brain.
"We believe that by using gene therapy and therapeutic viruses, we can target human neurons and make them temporarily sensitive to ultrasound signals used in clinical treatment to treat neurological diseases," Chalasani said.
He added that the method would also be used in the treatment of muscle and insulin-producing cells.
