Apple has had a yo-yo effect.
It's all the displays.
A more powerful processor, a higher-resolution camera, a stronger chassis, or a touch-recognition display are, in short, the virtues of the recently introduced ninth-generation iPhones.
The last two also have a negative impact on the dimensions and weights of the iPhone 6s and 6s Plus.
Apple's trend so far has been that every new generation of iPhone is lighter than the previous one.
Only the third and fourth generations were an exception, whose weight increased slightly compared to previous iPhones.
The two-gram difference in weight to the new product was really negligible.
However, this is far from the case with new iPhones.
Compared to last year's iPhone 6 and 6 Plus, the weight of the smaller model increased by 14 grams, and for the larger one by a full 20 grams.
On the one hand, it is no wonder that last year's affair of bending in Apple's pockets was a considerable torment.
The novelty chassis is made of a more durable aluminum alloy 7000, which was also reflected in the weight.
But displays have a much greater impact on it.
Apple has used 3D Touch technology to make displays recognize the power of touch.
To do this, the display had to be equipped with an additional layer of capacitive sensors.
The weight of the displays of new iPhones has thus more than doubled compared to previous generations.
For a smaller iPhone, from originally 12 grams to 29 grams, in the case of a larger one, from 19 to 40 grams.
With the iPhone 6s, the display is the heaviest component used.
The weight of only 143 grams is then achieved with this novelty thanks to the fat-off of the pee, which touched most of the remaining components.
For a larger model, the most difficult element used is the battery, but its weight has not changed from its predecessor.
Even in this case, the biggest increase is evident in the display.
The weight of the 5.5" iPhone 6s Plus thus reaches 192 grams.
How practical the new display technology will be will only become apparent during use.
First-time users will be able to try it out as early as Friday, September 25, when iPhone 6s and 6s Plus sales will begin in select countries.
Have the breakfast flakes been champions for tens of thousands of years?
In Grotta Paglicci, Italy, archaeologists have succeeded in finding a find that opens up interesting possibilities.
They discovered traces of modern man's settlement from different eras, including murals, tool residues and so on and so on.
But in layer 23A, which according to the tools dates back about 30,000 years, scientists have discovered something that is very reminiscent of the remnants of a breakfast buffet.
Traces of oat grains were found on the spot, which apparently went through the process of making such popular flakes.
During it, the grains are first soaked today, then dryed, removed from the packaging, the so-called regiment, then steamed and pressed flat.
Grains that appear to have been heated or scalded were discovered in the Paglicci Cave, and then probably crushed between two millstones - at least that's what the traces of use on the two stones in the cave suggest.
Thus, scientists were unable to prove in their publication for the journal PNAS that there was a complete process of making flakes in the cave, but the similarity is indeed very striking.
We also have no evidence of how people could eat flakes, but the assumption that it was with some liquid and quite possibly warm is, of course, quite logical.
At the same time, it is a very interesting proof of how intensively people used cereals long before the emergence of agriculture.
If the flake interpretation is correct, the oldest flakes have overtaken agriculture by about twenty thousand years.
