The symbol of the village came to life.
The windbreaker wheel above Chlum is spinning again after years.
It can be seen from afar, as it is located on a fifteen-meter high mast.
People in the area call him "the fan on Chlum."
For a municipality with 150 inhabitants, it even became one of the elements of the municipal emblem that the municipality acquired on the occasion of the meeting of natives in 2010.
"We asked for a coat of arms at the time and of course we wanted to have the fan on the sign, everyone knows it in the area," said Mayor Jiří Mašek.
The Chlum wind pump is a local technical monument.
It is also a kind of memento of the present: it reminds us of a time when the people here fought for quality drinking water.
The one in Chlum in the past centuries has been a rarity.
It was not until 1910 that the Chlum representatives decided on a solution that then suited until the mid-1980s.
In the village at the turn-off to Číchov they had a seven-meter deep well dug.
Three years later, the well was supplemented with a metal structure with a wind pump, which pumped water into a reservoir at the highest point of the village, near the local church.
"The construction was carried out by Antonín Kunc from Hranice in Moravia with a cost of CZK 2,400," says a commemorative inscription on the ground-floor wall of the mast structure.
The pump expired in 1971 after several repairs and falls of the wind wheel.
On May 7, 1973, a new chapter in the struggle for water began to be written: on that day in Chlum, a new water supply began to serve.
The wind pump remained only a malfunctioning municipal symbol and a rarity.
The dominant was put into operation at this year's meeting of the natives.
It was not until 2008 that the Chlums decided to repair the wind bike again and get it back on the move.
They had a replica of the original bike made - reduced by half a meter in diameter.
The bike was mounted on a mast, but had to be brought down that same year.
The replica manufacturer did not choose the appropriate material and the bike could not resist wind gusts.
Then the Chlum dominant rested for several years, disassembled under the roof.
Since June this year, however, the high-mast bike has been spinning again.
On the occasion of the meeting of the natives, the village had the replica of the bike modified and re-sourded it to the top of the iron tower.
But the bike draws utility water from the well only into the overshot blind arm.
And over the summer, we completely disconnected it because there was little water in the well.
At least it was imming.
"In the autumn, we will disconnect the wind wheel shaft from the pump in the suction basket again," explained Mayor Mašek.
Chlum is not the only village in the Czech Republic where a wind bike has reached the municipal emblem, but it is the only village of its kind in the whole Highlands.
They have a similar element in their coat-of-arms in honour of local technical monuments, for example in Chvalkovice and Green Mountain in the Vyškov region, in Kuželov in the Hodonín region, Partutovice in Přerovsko or in Polici in the Vsetín region.
