In their most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve policymakers will spend two days this week seated at Honduran's 27-foot mahogany table, deciding whether the time has come to raise a key interest rate after nearly a decade.
Towering above them at one end of the central bank ornament, the two-story meeting room will be a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the nation's economic interests above all else.
The central bank has a dual charge from Congress: maximizing American employment and keeping prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, Fed officials have acknowledged that there is an unwritten third term: financial stability.
And this third term could be an X-factor too close to the predictable decision to be announced On Thursday, whether the US economy is ready to start weaning off unprecedented stimulus in the form of near-zero short-term interest rates on the ground since late 2008.
Although most data show solid economic growth, recent turbulence in world financial markets could already scare the cautious Fed into adding to volatility by raising its benchmark federal funds rate - no more than a quarter of a percentage point.
"It is clear that the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing to watch in the first place," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage Stifel Nicolaus &Co.
"But I think they were just looking for an excuse not to increase the rate, the heightened uncertainty surrounding the global market already gives them sufficient justification to wait further," she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is causing nervousness in financial markets.
About half of economists recently surveyed by Blomberg predicted a rate hike this week.
But financial markets expect the Fed to delay the issue, with only about a 30% chance of an increase.
This would point to a stock market decline if the Fed raises rates only if policymakers soften the decline by promising that further increases are in sight.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average jumped 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The rally was triggered by expectations that Fed policymakers would hold rates steady this week, says John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be a surprise if the Fed raises rates now," he says.
If Fed policymakers did, "they would have to go to extremes in their program statement and hold hands with financial markets so they don't panic."
Other experts argued that raising rates would calm financial markets by removing uncertainty about how the Fed would proceed.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared well on its way to raising the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the US economic recovery.
Yellen said she expects to raise rates this year through spring and early summer, despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the labor market has seen solid growth this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% the previous month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to what the Fed considers full employment.
Wage gains showed signs of pick-up.
And while inflation continues to be below the central bank's annual 2% target, Fed policymakers argue that the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the tightness in the labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world began to squam down late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell as much as 16% below its record in May as investors feared that China's slowing economy would drag down global growth.
The market rebounded somewhat this month, and the Dow is now losing only nearly 10% of its May high.
For Fed policymakers, the turmoil in the market gives a comprehensive calculation of when to start raising interest rates.
"In the absence of what has happened in financial markets and reports of weakness in the Chinese economy in the last few weeks, there would have been a tightening at this meeting," said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now he predicts that they will wait at least a month to gain better control over the consequences.
"There's a lot of uncertainty about the impact this will have on the US economy, and they have almost no data to rely on for the latest developments in China," Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the Fed's main interests, so technically it should not be included in their decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the monetary authority of the whole world.
The central bank's influence in recent years has been enormous.
The mere suggestion by then-Chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed might "narrow" their monetary expansion in the market triggered convulsions around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly closely interconnected, Fed officials can be expected to follow developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central bankers and experts to better understand the state of the global economy.
Their decision-making process is "more art than science," said Zachary Karabell, head of global wealth-management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., noted this month that "the Fed has a history of exaggerated financial market movements that seem incoherent with economic fundamentals."
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee's policy-making committee, which pushed for a rate hike, cited the 1998-99 decision as an example.
The financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to lower its benchmark rate by 0.75 percentage points over three sessions "Despite limited identifiable effects on US growth," Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reversed those cuts.
The Fed should prioritize concerns about financial stability only during a major crisis like the market meltdown of 2008, said Adam Posen S., a former member of the Bank of England's rate-setting committee.
The latest turmoil is not even close to that level, he said.
"You certainly don't want to be in a situation of fear of a rate hike because the markets are upset," said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics .
The Federal Reserve Act still has a dual mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until that changes, I don't think they should get to the top.
