Speed on highways will stay the same.
The acceleration to 150 km/h was rejected by the Chamber of Deputies.
On selected sections of motorways it will not be possible to increase the maximum speed limit up to 150 km/h under favourable conditions.
On Tuesday, the House made the decision by agreeing to a Senate amendment that rejected the speed increase.
The amendment to the Road Act will now head to the President.
President Miloš Zeman had already said at the end of April that he would veto a law allowing a 150-kilometre speed.
Transport Minister Dan Ťok (for YES) was also opposed to the increase, according to which the Czech motorway network is not yet built for such a speed.
Ťok supported the Senate version of the bill in front of MPs on Tuesday.
The approved amendment will now allow speed increases from 90 to 110 kilometres per hour on selected first-class roads, especially four-current ones, in line with the government's original proposal.
The House first extended this option to highways that could be used in selected sections at speeds of up to 150 km/h, but the Senate refused.
Members have now accepted his proposal.
Senators, with the approval of the Minister of Transport, also removed from the amendment the right of the traffic police to have the last say in the regulation of local roads, which are taken care of by municipalities.
The Senate version, which was approved by the House, also provides for sewers, water pipes or public lighting cables to be stored longitudinally beneath the road surface.
Municipalities would thus save money on the purchase of land.
Municipalities should also not be obliged to take care of road vegetation along local roads, regardless of the owner of the land in use.
The amendment is also intended to help improve road protection and make it easier for municipalities to deal with towed vehicles to which owners do not subscribe.
Municipalities could now sell towed vehicles that their owners do not claim within six months of notification of the tow.
Municipalities will also be able to exclude transit freight traffic through their territory on second- and third-class roads under the threat of fines even for forwarding companies.
The amendment also abolishes the possibility of introducing electronic vignettes instead of existing paper vignettes, which will continue to be used after 1 January next year.
According to the government, this will save money on the introduction of an electronic system.
