Weight loss surgery could be useful for mildly obese diabetics
The benefits of weight loss surgery for slightly obese people with type 2 diabetes can last at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is still too early to say whether slightly obese people with type 2 diabetes live longer after weight loss surgery than those receiving non-surgical treatment.
"Mortality data takes a long time to display," says Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight loss surgery who wrote an editorial on the new study of JAMA surgery.
Weight loss operations, bariatric surgery use different methods to shrink the stomach.
Reducing hunger and limiting the human body to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most of the research has been conducted on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 25 or higher.
A BMI that measures the relationship of weight in relation to height is considered normal at values between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or higher indicates an overweight person, and people over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For their new studies, researchers from Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan have used data collected from a 2007 study that looks at two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and gastrectomy - in type 3 diabetes treatments in people who were slightly obese.
The average BMI among those who underwent surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of their fifth year, according to the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of those who were not given surgical treatment for diabetes remained roughly the same at 29.
Among patients with surgery, diabetes was solved completely in 36 percent and partly in 28 cases.
In the drug-treated group, only 1 percent and partially only about 2 percent of patients were completely resolved for diabetes comparison.
Furthermore, control of blood pressure, trigylcerides and "bad" LDL cholesterol was shown to be "generally better in the surgical group," the authors found.
The researchers also monitored the patient's blood haemoglobin A1c levels, which reflect ongoing blood sugar levels in the body.
Hemoglobin A1c is best maintained below 7 percent, researchers report.
After surgery, the average haemoglobin A1c dropped from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
However, in the drug-treated group, this figure remained at about 8 percent.
But this better "glycemic control" - reflected in better levels of hemoglobin A1c - did not reduce mortality in five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research team also compared average results with two types of operations.
After the fifth year, the bypass group lost more weight compared to the gastrectomy group (18.7 vs. 14.2 kg), achieved greater decreases in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 percent vs. 2.1 percent), and were more likely to relapse diabetes (46.9 percent vs. 16.7 percent).
While the new study does not show an improvement in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from studying stronger people in Sweden, where they found that surgery leads to prolonged life, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona College or Medicine-Phoenix.
According to a Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery had about a 29 percent greater chance of survival over the next 15 years, compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
While the new study did not show an improvement in survival among post-surgical patients, according to Blackstone, it is a reassuring result for people with bmi under 35 who are interested in these procedures.
"This is where this work is critical because it states that surgery is safer in a lower BMI group," without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, he says.
