Xi calls for opening up economy to wider world
It is necessary to open up the economy to the wider world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told the group tasked with reforming governance on Tuesday.
"China should engage in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improve open policies," the central head of the group for deepening overall reform said at the 16th meeting.
Promoting opening up in nascent reforms will give new impetus and vitality, as well as new room for economic growth, Xi says.
The lead group adopted a number of directives, including a negative list of regulatory market access, the relaxation of border control policy, support for state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to absorb private capital and the reorganisation of the registration resident system.
The statement states that a negative list will be drawn up identifying sectors and businesses that are outside the investment limits.
This system will be gradually tested and improved through testing programs.
The move is significant because it will give the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensuring a legal business environment and making the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also loosen controls on the powers it delegates to firms and make sure that companies themselves decide how to run their business.
The statement also states that China will allow border areas to discover new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
In an effort to open up the state-controlled sector, more areas will be open to private investment.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of companies that are financed from abroad and will provide them with better services," the statement said.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a "green card," by optimizing the requirements and simplifying the application process.
Ensuring the rights of lawyers to practice and develop professional judges and prosecutors was also discussed at the meeting.
Premier Li Keqiang and leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli also attended the meeting, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
New inpatient wards may be created in the Karlovy Vary Region.
According to the Deputy Governor of the Karlovy Vary Region Jakub Wowk (ČSSD), the current capacity of the inpatient departments of two regional hospitals and two private hospitals in the region is sufficient and partial adjustments should be made on the basis of an agreement between the departments of individual hospitals.
However, there are also possibilities of expanding care in the region.
For example, in surgical departments, one-day surgical centers could be established, where, according to the set concept, surgical procedures that do not require hospitalization for more than 24 hours would be performed.
It is not yet clear which specific hospitals should be focused on one-day surgery.
In turn, a laser center with the possibility of using laser technology for skin diseases could be created at the skin department of the Karlovy Vary Hospital.
The concept also recommended the creation of an atpalic center to care for patients with brain disabilities who are in a vegetative state.
Such a centre should be set up centrally and should be an integral part of the anaesthesiology-resuscitation department.
There is also the possibility of concentrating such a facility in ostrov hospital, where similar care already exists.
Another inpatient capacity that seems insufficient in the Karlovy Vary Region are after-care beds, especially beds of the Long-Term Sick Treatment Center (LDN), whose capacity in Nejdk is insufficient and, above all, should be closely linked to acute care beds.
Part of this facility should function as rehabilitation beds and part as classic LDN beds, the concept recommends.
As he points out, after-care beds are mainly missing in the Karlovy Vary Hospital.
There you could use the buildings left after centralization.
Last but not least, social health beds with a focus on the treatment of Alzheimer's disease are absent in the Karlovy Vary Region.
These beds are in short supply throughout the country, so they could also serve as an Alzheimer's centre for other regions.
According to the recommendations, hospitals should also prepare for the introduction of so-called follow-up beds, for which European subsidies will be released.
"These are beds that will follow the fields of supespecialized care and will form a space for the translation of patients after surgery, for example, after cardiothoracic, neurosurgical, transplant or other procedures," describes the regional concept of inpatient care.
New services could also be offered in the field of psychiatric care.